<p>The River Dart is one of the most ecologically sensitive estuaries in Devon. Designated as an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty and home to a rich diversity of native marine and estuarine species, it's an environment where human activity and natural systems coexist in a delicate balance. One of the less obvious threats to that balance arrives attached to the hulls of boats — invasive non-native species transported unknowingly from harbour to harbour by recreational and commercial vessels.</p>

<h2>How Hull Fouling Spreads Invasive Species</h2>

<p>The mechanism is straightforward. A boat visiting Dartmouth from, say, Plymouth or Falmouth may arrive with organisms attached to its hull that are present in the departure harbour but not yet established in the Dart. These hitchhikers — fragments of colonial organisms, larvae, reproductive material — detach naturally or are removed during cleaning, introducing them into a new environment. If the conditions suit them, they colonise and establish, potentially outcompeting native species that have no evolved defence against the newcomer.</p>

<p>This isn't a theoretical risk. The Marine Biological Association and Natural England have documented the spread of several invasive species along the south coast of England, with hull fouling identified as a primary vector. Dart Harbour Authority has explicitly referenced this risk in their environmental guidance, encouraging boat owners to clean their hulls regularly and responsibly.</p>

<h2>Invasive Species of Concern in the Dart Area</h2>

<p>Several invasive non-native species have been identified in or near the River Dart catchment area:</p>

<p><strong>Carpet sea squirt (<em>Didemnum vexillum</em>):</strong> Originally from the Pacific, this colonial ascidian forms thick, carpet-like mats over hard surfaces — including pontoons, ropes, and hulls. It smothers native communities and is extremely difficult to eradicate once established. It has been found in several south coast harbours and there is ongoing monitoring for its presence in the Dart.</p>

<p><strong>Pacific oyster (<em>Magallana gigas</em>):</strong> Introduced deliberately for aquaculture, Pacific oysters have spread to wild habitats across the south coast. While they don't typically travel on hulls as adults, their larvae can be present in ballast water and fouling communities. Their aggressive colonisation of intertidal areas can displace native oyster populations and alter habitat structure.</p>

<p><strong>Wireweed (<em>Sargassum muticum</em>):</strong> A Japanese brown alga that arrived in British waters via imported oyster stock. It grows rapidly, forming dense floating canopies that reduce light for native seagrass beds and alter water flow patterns. Hull fouling is a documented dispersal mechanism for this species.</p>

<p><strong>Chinese mitten crab (<em>Eriocheir sinensis</em>):</strong> While not directly transported on hulls, this invasive estuarine crab has been found in several Devon rivers and its spread highlights the vulnerability of estuarine ecosystems like the Dart to non-native introductions.</p>

<h2>Why the Dart Is Particularly Vulnerable</h2>

<p>Estuaries are inherently more vulnerable to invasive species than open coastal waters. The Dart's mix of freshwater and saltwater creates a range of salinity zones, each with its own ecological community. A single invasive species adapted to brackish conditions can find a foothold in the estuary that it wouldn't find in fully marine waters.</p>

<p>The Dart's role as a popular cruising destination amplifies the risk. During summer, the river hosts a constant stream of visiting yachts arriving from harbours across the English Channel and beyond. Each arrival is a potential introduction event. And because the Dart's estuarine conditions are relatively unusual compared to the open-harbour marinas that many visiting yachts come from, there's a meaningful chance that organisms arriving on visiting hulls will encounter conditions they're pre-adapted to thrive in.</p>

<h2>What Boat Owners Can Do</h2>

<p>The good news is that regular hull cleaning is one of the most effective things an individual boat owner can do to reduce their contribution to invasive species spread. The key principles are:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Clean before you move.</strong> If you're planning to move your boat from one harbour to another, clean your hull before departure. This removes fouling organisms before they have a chance to be transported to a new environment.</li>
  <li><strong>Clean responsibly.</strong> Cleaning must capture the removed material — if fouling containing invasive organisms is scraped off into the water, you've solved nothing. Our Keelcrab Bag system captures all debris, ensuring nothing re-enters the estuary during cleaning.</li>
  <li><strong>Clean regularly.</strong> Frequent cleaning prevents fouling communities from becoming established on your hull in the first place. A hull cleaned every 2-3 months rarely carries the kind of mature, diverse fouling community that poses the highest biosecurity risk.</li>
  <li><strong>Report unusual growth.</strong> If you notice unfamiliar organisms on your hull during a haul-out or inspection, report them. Dart Harbour Authority, Devon Wildlife Trust, and the Marine Biological Association all welcome sightings of potentially invasive species.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Our Role in Biosecurity</h2>

<p>At HullSafe, we see our role as part of the biosecurity infrastructure of the harbours we operate in. Every hull we clean is a hull that's less likely to transport invasive organisms. Every cleaning visit that captures debris in the Keelcrab Bag is a visit that keeps that material out of the water column. And every HD inspection that documents unusual growth patterns contributes to the monitoring data that harbour authorities and environmental agencies need.</p>

<p>It's not glamorous, and it's not what most boat owners think about when they book a hull clean. But it's a meaningful contribution to protecting one of Devon's most valuable estuarine environments — and it costs nothing extra beyond the cleaning you'd be doing anyway.</p>

